In France, voting is traditionally a low tech experience: voters isolate themselves in a cabin and put a preprinted paper sheet on which the candidate of their choice is registered in an envelope.
After the officials have confirmed the identity of the voter, the voter throws the envelope into the ballot box and signs the list of voters.
The French election law sets the process quite strictly.
Since 1988, ballot boxes must be transparent so that voters and observers can testify that no envelopes are present at the start of the election and that no envelopes are cast, except those of properly counted and authorized voters.
