The Sundarbans are the largest mangrove belt in the world and stretch over 80 km from the Bangladeshi and Indian hinterland to the coast.
The Sundarbans were declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site and the part of the forest that lies within the Indian territory is called the Sundarbans National Park.
However, the forests are not only mangroves, they include some of mangroves, but also some of the last remaining holdings of the powerful jungle that once covered the Ganges.
The Sundarbans cover an area of 3,850 km², of which one third is covered by water and marches.
The Sundarbans have been a nature reserve since 1966, and it is estimated that 400 Bengal royal tigers and about 30,000 spotted deer are now kept there.
